# 1- Getting the data from InterSystems IRIS

paragraphs.title: Introduction
paragraphs.text:
%md 

This notebook has been created having Scala as the standard programming language. 

But we still need to use %spark magic to have a spark context automatically created for us.

On the first notebook of this series, we took a look at the data model and we saw that there was a 
transactions table named *IRISDemo.BC_TRANSACTIONS* with two columns: *BC_TRANS_SRC_ACC* and *BC_TRANS_DEST_ACC*.

These columns point to tables *IRISDemo.BC_MERCH_ACCOUNT* and *IRISDemo.BC_CUST_ACCOUNT*. Let's try to build a
single data set with all this data joined so we can give a good look at the quality of our data:

paragraphs.title: Reading the data from IRIS
paragraphs.text:
%spark

val df = spark.read.iris("""select 
    c.BC_ACC_CUST_AGE as age,
    c.BC_ACC_CUST_GENDER as gender,
    t.BC_TRANS_AMOUNT as amount,
    t.BC_TRANS_IS_FRAUD as fraud,
    m.ID as merchant,
    m.BC_MERCH_CATEGORY as category
from 
    IRISDemo.BC_TRANSACTIONS t, 
    IRISDemo.BC_MERCH_ACCOUNT m, 
    IRISDemo.BC_CUST_ACCOUNT c 
where 
    t.BC_TRANS_DEST_ACC=m.ID and 
    t.BC_TRANS_SRC_ACC=c.ID and 
    t.BC_TRANS_TYPE='PAYMENT'""")
    
df.cache()
df.count()

# 2 - Unbalanced data

msg.data: 2 - Unbalanced data

paragraphs.text:
%md

An unbalaced data set is problematic because training will be biased to the dominant class (not a fraud in this case). 
We will have to compensate for this later. 

A simple look at the number of frauds compared to genuine transactions is enough to see that this is a highly unbalanced data set:

%md

# 3 - Should we use feature selection?

msg.data: 3 - Should we use feature selection?

paragraphs.title: Feature Selection - Testing for Independence
paragraphs.text:
%md

Feature selection is an important problem in Machine learning. There are many feature selection methods available such as mutual information, information gain, and chi square test.

We have 500K transactions. The *fraud* field will tell us if a transaction is marked as fraud or not. We have many features (age, gender, amount, merchant and category) but we are not
sure which features have an impact in *fraud* class. Given a feature X, we can use Chi Square Test to evaluate its importance to distinguish the class. 

By calculating the Chi square scores for all the features, we can rank the features by the chi square scores, then choose the top ranked features for model training. In other words, 
the higher value of the \chi^2 score, the more likelihood the feature is correlated with the class, thus it should be selected for model training.

%md

So, Chi2 thinks that practically all dimensions are important. We haven't tested amount yet because it is not a categorical dimension. 
The idea would be to take the most important features. We used python mllib to calculate Chi2. Bellow, we will use Spark's ChiSqSelector
to do this job for us and pick the right features for us automatically. If all features are important, taking just some of them may actually
hurt the model... Let's see.

## 5.2 - Random Forest Classifier - Training the model with all features

msg.data: 5.2 - Random Forest Classifier - Training the model with all features

paragraphs.title: 5.2.1 - Training the Model without using Chi2 feature selection
paragraphs.text:
%spark.pyspark

# We will not specify parametrers by hand. We will use a parameter grid to allow for many combinations of parameters
# to be evaluated. 
#rf = RandomForestClassifier(labelCol="fraud", featuresCol="features", numTrees=10)
rf = RandomForestClassifier(labelCol="fraud", featuresCol="features")

# We must create the pipeline first. Then we will run this pipeline many times, 
# with different estimator parameres given by a ParamGridBuilder
pipelineRF = Pipeline() \
    .setStages([vectorAssembler, rf])

paramGridRF = ParamGridBuilder() \
             .addGrid(rf.maxDepth, [2, 5, 10]) \
             .addGrid(rf.maxBins, [10, 20, 30]) \
             .addGrid(rf.numTrees, [5, 10]) \
             .build()

# The CrossValidator will split the training data into 3 (numFolds) sets of training data. Each with will be splitted in
# a sub-training-set and a sub-testing-set. That will help reducing overfitting. Then, the CrossValidator will use
# the paramGrid to test different configurations of the estimator (the training algorithm) on the three sets of data.
# The CrossValidator needs a way to evaluate the results. That is the function of the evaluator. The evaluator will
# be evaluate the final predictions of each resulting model. The CrossValidator will them compare the results and pick
# the configuration that worked best.
evaluatorRF = MulticlassClassificationEvaluator(labelCol="fraud")

# Create 3-fold CrossValidator combining the model pipeline + paramGrid + evaluator:
cvRF = CrossValidator(estimator=pipelineRF, estimatorParamMaps=paramGridRF, evaluator=evaluatorRF, numFolds=2)

# Run cross validations.  This can take about 6 minutes
cvModelRF = cvRF.fit(trainingData)
